(located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Spine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): from Middle English <i>spice</i> ‘spice’ (Old French <i>espice</i>), perhaps a nickname for a dealer in spices or an apothecary. See   Spicer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Spicer","meanings":["English (London and Kent): occupational name from Middle English <i>spicer</i> ‘dealer in spices, apothecary’ (Old French <i>espicier</i>, <i>especier</i>, Late Latin <i>speciarius</i>, an agent derivative of <i>species</i> ‘spice, groceries, merchandise’). See   Spice  .","Jewish (from Poland): variant of   Spitzer  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":25,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de la Spine II of Coughton was born about 1234, in Warwickshire, England, his father, Roger de 